               <interp inst="t18440205-800" type="date" value="18440205"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-800-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-800-18440205 t18440205-800-offence-1 t18440205-800-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>800. <persName id="def1-800-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-800-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-800-18440205" type="surname" value="GARDINER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-800-18440205" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM GARDINER</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440205-800-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-800-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-800-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp> for feloniously assaulting Thomas Lemon, and cutting and wounding him on the right cheek, with in<lb></lb>tent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS LEMON</hi>, <hi rend="italic">carman, Clark's-row, Brixton.</hi> On Monday evening, the 5th of Feb., between seven and eight o'clock, I was at Mr. Griffiths's yard, engaged in putting a horse into a stable—the prisoner, who is horse-keeper to Mr. Griffiths, had some words with me about the hone sweating—he told me it was a pretty way to bring a horse home—I said, "I know how to drive a horse, without your directing me"—he directly said he would beat me out of the stable, and beat my head off—I told him he had better do it—I went and hung my whip up, and he took up the bottom of a sconce of a stable lantern, and sent it at me, as I went out of the stable—it caught the side of my cheek and ear—I was blinded with blood almost immediately—I thought my eye was out almost—I told him I would give him into custody—he said he did not care if he had knocked my head off, or brains out, I will not be sure which—I got a policeman, and gave him into custody—I have</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050224"></xptr>
               <p>been affected by this from that time—I had it dressed—I have suffered weak<lb></lb>ness from loss of blood, and been in great pain—it is getting easier now—this is the sconce—(<hi rend="italic">produced.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You had overworked the horse? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was very slippery—I had not been drinking—I had but one pint of beer all the afternoon—we had not been drinking together—he did not look as if he had been drinking—I had been in Mr. Griffiths's employ, off and on, three or four years, and the prisoner seven or eight—I was not angry with him—I told him if there was anything amiss to speak to Mr. Griffiths about it—I was not saucy—he said a great many aggravating words to me—he repeatedly said he would knock my head off, and I said he might do it if he thought proper—I had said nothing to him before that—I swear I did not offer to do any thing to him—there was a long candle in the sconce just lighted—he was three or four yards from me—after the injury he told me to go to a doctor—he did not say in my hearing that he would pay the expenses, or that he was very sorry that I was hurt—he said he would pay the dressing of it—nothing has been done but putting some plaster on it, and keeping it clean—I have spit blood, and blood has run out of my nose ever since it has been done.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1487" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1487" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1487" type="surname" value="SALTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1487" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMBS SALTER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 15.) I searched the shed at Mr. Griffiths's yard, and found this sconce on the ground, apparently concealed by chaff and dust.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1488" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1488" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1488" type="surname" value="MURPHY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1488" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MURPHY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 261.) I took the prisoner into cus<lb></lb>tody—I told him what for—he resisted very much.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was it soon after the complaint? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About a quarter of an hour.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1489" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1489" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1489" type="surname" value="PRICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1489" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN PRICE</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a chemist's-shop. Isaw the prosecutor's cheek, he had a contused and incised wound, about an inch below the orbit—it was not a bad wound—there appeared to have been a good deal of blood from it—it is not likely to do him any permanent injury.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18440205-800-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
